00:05:37.679 --> 00:05:40.040
So how do we achieve this scalable outcome?

00:05:40.040 --> 00:05:43.359
Well, we did it using data science, of course.

00:05:43.359 --> 00:05:48.799
We used a flexible framework strategy in which data science is the key to the impactful AI

00:05:48.799 --> 00:05:51.100
that we use to accelerate everything.

00:05:51.100 --> 00:05:56.040
And so if one way of thinking about data science is starting at the end and working backwards,

00:05:56.040 --> 00:06:00.000
particularly if you want to be impactful, and as we all are data scientists here, if

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:03.200
you don't want to waste your time.

00:06:03.200 --> 00:06:07.679
So one definition of data science is the use of computational approaches, automation,

00:06:07.679 --> 00:06:14.519
AI, ML, to enable specific decisions towards desired outcomes.

00:06:14.519 --> 00:06:16.320
And so what do I mean by an outcome?

00:06:16.320 --> 00:06:21.640
Well, some sort of improvement in a context or area that you can only achieve by taking

00:06:21.640 --> 00:06:24.679
an action, by expending resources.

00:06:24.679 --> 00:06:28.640
But you only expend the resources that you decide to expend and not the ones that you

00:06:28.640 --> 00:06:29.640
don't.

00:06:29.640 --> 00:06:33.799
And you only make that decision once you have achieved sufficient confidence by reducing

00:06:33.799 --> 00:06:36.079
the ambiguity surrounding all of your options.

00:06:36.079 --> 00:06:41.920
And you only do that once you've gotten enough information about what likely cause-effect

00:06:41.920 --> 00:06:43.160
relationships could exist.

00:06:43.160 --> 00:06:48.399
And you only do that once you ask the right questions, attempt to eliminate those gaps

00:06:48.399 --> 00:06:52.880
that can make it easier to understand potential causality.

00:06:52.880 --> 00:07:00.559
So with that in mind, data science and artificial intelligence have this software intersection

00:07:00.559 --> 00:07:03.299
that define the relationship between the two of them.

00:07:03.299 --> 00:07:08.799
So whereas data science is using data to figure out which decisions to make, artificial intelligence

00:07:08.799 --> 00:07:13.959
is simulating autonomous, basically execution of those decisions.

00:07:13.959 --> 00:07:17.200
So simulating human thinking, reasoning, and behavior.

00:07:17.200 --> 00:07:22.000
So you can have artificial intelligence systems in which you directly tell the computer what

00:07:22.119 --> 00:07:26.000
the decision-making rules are, but you can have other artificial intelligence systems

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:31.720
that use machine learning in which the computer figures out the decision-making rules by understanding

00:07:31.720 --> 00:07:33.359
the data itself.

00:07:33.359 --> 00:07:39.299
And then deep learning, of course, is making computer use multiple layers of thought in

00:07:39.299 --> 00:07:43.040
order to figure out what the decision-making rules should be.

00:07:43.040 --> 00:07:48.760
So in this data science framework, you basically start at the end and you define what that

00:07:48.760 --> 00:07:49.760
outcome is.

00:07:49.799 --> 00:07:54.920
And then you work towards identifying the obstacles towards that outcome and then eliminating

00:07:54.920 --> 00:07:56.019
those obstacles.

00:07:56.019 --> 00:08:00.320
And that's one of the ways that you can maximize your efficiency and also have staying power

00:08:00.320 --> 00:08:03.880
in terms of the impact of what you do.

00:08:03.880 --> 00:08:09.000
But basically this means that data science is essentially decision science, which really

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:12.619
if you think about it is just minimizing ambiguity.

00:08:12.619 --> 00:08:17.480
So if you just do a little mini quick exercise in your head right now, and you think about

00:08:17.480 --> 00:08:22.119
if you were to try to pick between the two roads that are shown here, so just pick the

00:08:22.119 --> 00:08:25.239
right one, like what would you pick?

00:08:25.239 --> 00:08:29.519
You can't because you don't really know anything about either of the two roads.

00:08:29.519 --> 00:08:30.940
There's too much ambiguity.

00:08:30.940 --> 00:08:36.119
And so none of us are confident enough to pick one road over the other.

00:08:36.119 --> 00:08:39.280
We don't have enough justification to decide on either.

00:08:39.280 --> 00:08:43.280
Now if the decision threshold were pretty low, so maybe some of you did pick, and that

00:08:43.280 --> 00:08:45.880
might be because you're thinking, well, it doesn't really matter, nothing bad is going

00:08:45.880 --> 00:08:46.960
to happen to me.

00:08:46.960 --> 00:08:50.799
But if it's a higher risk, if something goes sideways and that it impacts something you

00:08:50.799 --> 00:08:55.599
really care about, then you're like, whoa, whoa, whoa, I actually need more information.

00:08:55.599 --> 00:09:00.080
So if you find out, for example, that down one of the roads, there's some sort of danger,

00:09:00.080 --> 00:09:06.080
well, at least now you've reduced the ambiguity about one of the roads and increased the confidence

00:09:06.080 --> 00:09:08.760
that you may have about what you should do.

00:09:08.760 --> 00:09:10.400
So now you have a little bit more confidence.

00:09:10.400 --> 00:09:14.159
And if there's only two roads, one of them is definitely dangerous, well, maybe you could

00:09:14.159 --> 00:09:18.320
go down the other road because now you have at least enough knowledge to decide on what

00:09:18.320 --> 00:09:19.599
you want to do.

00:09:19.599 --> 00:09:23.599
And so that takes you from being stuck, where you had that analysis paralysis in the absence

00:09:23.599 --> 00:09:27.080
of sufficient data, to being unstuck.

00:09:27.080 --> 00:09:31.559
And so that's the goal of data science, to help to reduce those obstacles so you can

00:09:31.559 --> 00:09:33.400
go from one to the other.

00:09:33.400 --> 00:09:40.840
So I want to walk through a couple examples of using some of this framework to make decisions

00:09:40.840 --> 00:09:42.760
in other collaborations that I've been involved in.

00:09:42.880 --> 00:09:50.679
And they're along the pipeline, as we may think of it as a pipeline, in terms of developing

00:09:50.679 --> 00:09:51.799
therapeutics.

00:09:51.799 --> 00:09:55.239
So ultimately, at the end, when you have a therapeutic, you want to give it to a patient.

00:09:55.239 --> 00:09:59.559
But you want to give it to the patient that has a disease that the therapeutic is the

00:09:59.559 --> 00:10:01.380
most appropriate for.

00:10:01.380 --> 00:10:06.520
So I'll talk about a couple of these examples and collaborations along this entire pipeline.

00:10:06.520 --> 00:10:12.000
So one desired outcome is that genetic disease patients are given the most accurate diagnosis

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:13.000
and treatments.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:19.520
So you need to pick between diagnosis A, diagnosis B, or diagnosis N, which could be 2,000, 3,000,

00:10:19.520 --> 00:10:20.520
10,000.

00:10:20.520 --> 00:10:23.159
The decisions are pretty complicated a lot of times.

00:10:23.159 --> 00:10:27.080
So I won't go into a lot of the details about how I did it, but you can check out the talks

00:10:27.080 --> 00:10:32.940
that I have on my YouTube channel at youtube.com slash at data-driven decision making.

00:10:32.940 --> 00:10:37.400
But some of the technologies that I used were ontologies, which are essentially hierarchical

00:10:37.400 --> 00:10:42.919
vocabularies, embedding-like annotations, which are links between entities and vectorial

00:10:42.919 --> 00:10:49.520
representations of ontology words as numbers, semantic similarity, which is matching using

00:10:49.520 --> 00:10:57.080
ontological annotations, and then transitive prioritization, which is guilt by association

00:10:57.080 --> 00:10:59.200
rank propagation.

00:10:59.200 --> 00:11:03.000
So another collaboration, so this is way on the earlier side of the spectrum.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:07.200
We were talking about assigning diagnoses to patients and then saying, well, since this

00:11:07.200 --> 00:11:11.239
is a diagnosis, then this is probably the appropriate therapeutic treatment.

00:11:11.239 --> 00:11:14.760
So on the other end of the spectrum, if you're saying, well, what therapy should we even

00:11:14.760 --> 00:11:16.599
develop in the first place?

00:11:16.599 --> 00:11:21.719
So one desired outcome of that is disease genes are targeted with the potentially most

00:11:21.719 --> 00:11:26.359
effective therapeutic modality that we have, and it's at Regeneron because this is where

00:11:26.359 --> 00:11:28.239
I work.

00:11:28.239 --> 00:11:34.000
So the technologies that I used to identify whether or not gene A is the right one to

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:40.039
target or gene B with a given modality were knowledge graphs, so an interconnected web

00:11:40.039 --> 00:11:44.799
of data, a Neo4j graph database, which is a knowledge graph server, that's where you

00:11:44.799 --> 00:11:51.640
can store the graph database, and Cypher, which is the query language that Neo4j uses.

00:11:51.640 --> 00:11:54.559
And they intentionally picked those names, by the way, because the creators were fans

00:11:54.559 --> 00:11:56.799
of The Matrix, which I love.

00:11:56.799 --> 00:12:05.359
So how did we apply this to scale mentor matching to Dr. Strange, our problem?

00:12:05.359 --> 00:12:10.320
The real question, actually, was what outcome did Magnetron AI need to be able to prioritize

00:12:10.320 --> 00:12:12.700
decision recommendations towards?

00:12:12.700 --> 00:12:17.119
And that outcome really is that employees in need of specific skills are matched with

00:12:17.119 --> 00:12:21.000
others who are best suited to help them develop those skills.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:25.359
So if we think about it, it's really that the decision is to match each mentee with

00:12:25.359 --> 00:12:27.239
the mentor that can provide the best help.

00:12:27.239 --> 00:12:32.780
So if we start at the end and work backwards, the end is the matching and the best, so matching

00:12:32.780 --> 00:12:35.080
of the mentee with the best mentor.

00:12:35.080 --> 00:12:40.159
And so if we work all the way backwards, we need the minimum necessary data to feel confident

00:12:40.159 --> 00:12:42.979
enough to say this is the pair that we want.

00:12:42.979 --> 00:12:47.359
And then in order to do that, we need to collect the requisite data.

00:12:47.359 --> 00:12:52.520
Now previously, they were using Microsoft Form at Regeneron, but we thought that we

00:12:52.520 --> 00:12:56.840
could streamline and keep the data a lot more consistent if we did this with a Shiny

00:12:56.840 --> 00:12:59.559
approach, which I'll get into in a bit.

00:12:59.559 --> 00:13:03.840
But fundamentally, the conversion between the answer and the recommended action is that

00:13:03.840 --> 00:13:06.919
decision engine that does the processing.

00:13:06.919 --> 00:13:11.619
So then the question for you all that you might be wondering is, how does the decision

00:13:11.619 --> 00:13:13.719
recommendation engine work?

00:13:13.719 --> 00:13:17.719
Well, fundamentally, it's two steps, filter and then sort.

00:13:17.719 --> 00:13:21.760
And the filtering is using a lot of the approaches that I mentioned earlier, and the sorting

00:13:21.760 --> 00:13:25.039
is using the other approaches that I mentioned earlier.

00:13:25.039 --> 00:13:28.400
And there's two parts to the filtering and one part to the sorting.

00:13:28.400 --> 00:13:32.840
So the first part of the filtering is cohort eligibility inference.

00:13:32.840 --> 00:13:36.359
And you can think of that as like a bouncer at the front door of a club.

00:13:36.359 --> 00:13:41.320
The second one is compatibility or match compatibility inference.

00:13:41.320 --> 00:13:46.200
So you can think of that as the bodyguard of a person sitting at a table inside of the

00:13:46.200 --> 00:13:47.200
club.

00:13:47.200 --> 00:13:48.919
So one is, are you allowed to even get into the cohort?

00:13:48.919 --> 00:13:51.440
And the other is, are you allowed to be a match?

00:13:51.440 --> 00:13:57.020
So the way cohort eligibility inference works is identifying eligible users, which are users

00:13:57.020 --> 00:14:02.200
that have any inclusion criteria minus users that have any exclusion criteria.

00:14:02.200 --> 00:14:07.840
And so the inclusion exclusion criteria membership is defined on the basis of username information,

00:14:07.840 --> 00:14:12.280
username lists, and reporting structure hierarchy.

00:14:12.280 --> 00:14:18.479
So these are taken into consideration when a cohort is designed by an administrator.

00:14:18.520 --> 00:14:23.640
In terms of the pair compatibility or match compatibility inference, this is asymmetric

00:14:23.640 --> 00:14:28.919
because you can think of it in terms of in the dating world outside of corporate America,

00:14:28.919 --> 00:14:31.559
there could be people who are interested in others.

00:14:31.559 --> 00:14:35.159
But just because one person is interested in 10 people doesn't mean that each of those

00:14:35.159 --> 00:14:37.679
10 people is interested in the one person.

00:14:37.679 --> 00:14:39.359
So there's asymmetry.

00:14:39.359 --> 00:14:45.440
And so this is what is taken into account with R and Shiny here.

00:14:45.440 --> 00:14:52.239
So the asymmetric compatible applicants are applicants with any inclusion criteria minus

00:14:52.239 --> 00:14:54.640
applicants with any exclusion criteria.

00:14:54.640 --> 00:14:57.479
And that's from the perspective of each applicant.

00:14:57.479 --> 00:15:01.299
So then if you take the perspective from each applicant and you have your asymmetric list,

00:15:01.299 --> 00:15:08.760
if you integrate these two lists, now you have your symmetric pair of eligible compatible

00:15:08.760 --> 00:15:10.679
people.

00:15:10.679 --> 00:15:18.400
And so this is computed in parallel and asynchronously via APIs, as was mentioned a bit earlier.

00:15:18.400 --> 00:15:26.119
And so it's using the same categories as before for the eligibility for applying to the cohort,

00:15:26.119 --> 00:15:30.080
but then additional things like years of experience and personal reporting line are allowed to

00:15:30.080 --> 00:15:33.000
be submitted by the applicants.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:35.200
And then the ranking part.

00:15:35.200 --> 00:15:43.640
So what's done here is a space symmetric calculation of skill similarity and activity distance

00:15:43.640 --> 00:15:48.159
between all pairs that have been applied to the cohort.

00:15:48.159 --> 00:15:52.200
And then the next step is to do an asymmetric calculation of the rank.

00:15:52.200 --> 00:15:56.919
So from each person's perspective, how much are the other people good matches for each

00:15:56.919 --> 00:15:59.599
member of a given pair?

00:15:59.599 --> 00:16:03.760
And then this is all brought together because then you calculate the average asymmetric

00:16:03.760 --> 00:16:08.200
rank and then rank that asymmetric rank that has been averaged.

00:16:08.200 --> 00:16:10.280
So now you have a global rank.

00:16:10.280 --> 00:16:12.200
This is being recorded so you can rewatch it.

00:16:12.200 --> 00:16:15.080
I'm so sorry.

00:16:15.080 --> 00:16:22.080
So what I ended up doing was democratizing Magnetron AI using R and Python.

00:16:22.080 --> 00:16:26.280
Python primarily for interacting with the large language model on the back, which I'm

00:16:26.280 --> 00:16:28.559
guessing some of you are curious about.

00:16:28.559 --> 00:16:33.960
But overall, the approach to democratizing these analytics are building a knowledge base

00:16:33.960 --> 00:16:38.960
and then building an API for interfacing with that knowledge base and then building a human

00:16:38.960 --> 00:16:40.640
friendly interface.

00:16:40.640 --> 00:16:44.719
So I use the model view controller paradigm, but you can use others, right?

00:16:44.719 --> 00:16:49.000
So the model, the view and the controller are essentially the different components where

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:55.159
you can have a user open the Shiny app that asks questions of the API, that asks questions

00:16:55.200 --> 00:17:00.440
of the model, that sends a response back to the API and then back to the user, which makes

00:17:00.440 --> 00:17:06.479
it easy for a human being to generate very complex queries and analyses on the back end

00:17:06.479 --> 00:17:08.160
without knowing how to program.

00:17:08.160 --> 00:17:12.920
And it makes it easier for the FAIR principles to be implemented, which makes things future

00:17:12.920 --> 00:17:17.520
proof and robust, findable, accessible, interoperable, and reusable.

00:17:17.520 --> 00:17:21.959
So I'm going to blaze through the user stories here, but this is really how it works in a

00:17:21.959 --> 00:17:22.959
nutshell.

00:17:22.959 --> 00:17:27.959
So someone creates a cohort and then people can apply to the custom URL that the Shiny

00:17:27.959 --> 00:17:29.880
app provides as a response.

00:17:29.880 --> 00:17:33.839
And then the Shiny app sends a notification to the approver that they have to approve

00:17:33.839 --> 00:17:35.079
the applications.

00:17:35.079 --> 00:17:39.439
And then once the applications are approved, if they are approved, the nominator can go

00:17:39.439 --> 00:17:44.400
in, click a single button, and then an asynchronous parallel process is triggered that generates

00:17:44.400 --> 00:17:47.359
all of those 80,000 possible pairs.

00:17:47.359 --> 00:17:50.920
And that are also ranked via the algorithm that I said before.

00:17:50.920 --> 00:17:57.239
And then a reviewer who may know about some of the pairs can provide the additional metadata

00:17:57.239 --> 00:18:02.599
so that the approvers can take that into consideration when they are either approving or rejecting

00:18:02.599 --> 00:18:04.040
the nominated pairs.

00:18:04.040 --> 00:18:09.719
If rejected, the nominators can replace the pairs.

00:18:09.719 --> 00:18:14.880
And then if they are approved, the notification goes to the mentee, which can also reject.

00:18:14.880 --> 00:18:19.719
But if it's accepted, then it's sent to the mentor and a final match is provided.

00:18:19.719 --> 00:18:24.520
And recently, we've also incorporated large language models into this where it generates

00:18:24.520 --> 00:18:28.199
custom recommendations on the basis of all the information that was provided by each

00:18:28.199 --> 00:18:29.920
of the members of the pair.

00:18:29.920 --> 00:18:36.199
So the result is a user-friendly Shiny app that makes it really easy for people to submit

00:18:36.199 --> 00:18:37.420
all their information.

00:18:37.420 --> 00:18:44.760
And it's a single source of controlled structured truth with data access controls in place.

00:18:44.760 --> 00:18:46.959
And the best part is that it's domain agnostic.

00:18:46.959 --> 00:18:52.479
So it's usable for the multiverse of possibilities that you could possibly have for matching

00:18:52.479 --> 00:18:55.839
people for institutional knowledge transfer.

00:18:55.839 --> 00:19:00.160
And so we've used it for our 400 plus person data science community of practice that I

00:19:00.160 --> 00:19:03.000
created at Regeneron.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:05.160
And yeah, that's really the summary.

00:19:05.160 --> 00:19:06.640
We had a worthwhile challenge.

00:19:06.640 --> 00:19:08.719
We hit it with an AI approach.

00:19:08.719 --> 00:19:13.719
And starting at the end and working backwards is what this team that I was able to work

00:19:13.719 --> 00:19:18.560
together with over the past two years used to build Magnetron AI.

